Watching a kitten fumbling around,

00:00:10.000 --> 00:00:15.120
it might feel as if you've never encountered anything so devastatingly adorable.

00:00:17.000 --> 00:00:21.864
In your mortal life. You may want to pet it soft fur and kiss its tiny head.

00:00:25.000 --> 00:00:32.168
But you may also feel the conflicting urge to squeeze, or smash the kitten, maybe even stuffed it in your mouth.

00:00:36.000 --> 00:00:39.712
However, you don't, and you might be appalled by yourself.

00:00:40.000 --> 00:00:43.520
But this urge which psychologists call cute aggression,

00:00:45.000 --> 00:00:49.800
is a surprisingly common one, estimated to affect about half of all adults.

00:00:52.000 --> 00:00:57.184
To better understand this peculiar phenomenon. Let's start with what cuteness is.

00:00:58.000 --> 00:01:06.000
In 1943 One scientists created a baby schema that identified key features associated with cuteness like plump cheeks, large eyes and short limbs.

00:01:11.000 --> 00:01:18.488
These characteristics associated with many young animals were placed in opposition with those perceived as less cute.

00:01:20.000 --> 00:01:24.800
Decades of study have since indicated that this baby schema reliably tracks

00:01:25.000 --> 00:01:27.267
with how people perceive cuteness.

00:01:28.000 --> 00:01:33.976
When study participants see images containing more features that the baby's schema pinpoints as cute,

00:01:34.000 --> 00:01:37.072
they tend to look at them longer and more often,

00:01:38.000 --> 00:01:43.440
and the photos appear to stimulate brain regions associated with emotion, and reward.

00:01:45.000 --> 00:01:48.008
Cuteness is also thought to influence behavior.

00:01:49.000 --> 00:01:57.000
In a 2009 study, participants performed better at the game operation, which demands precise careful movements when shown cute images beforehand.

00:02:00.000 --> 00:02:03.976
The results of another study indicated that people use recycling bins more

00:02:04.000 --> 00:02:12.000
when they have cute images on them. And the fact that cuteness hijacks our emotions is certainly not lost on authorities and advertisers.

00:02:15.000 --> 00:02:17.867
But why does cuteness have this hold on us?

00:02:19.000 --> 00:02:25.976
It's nearly impossible to know for sure. But one theory is that cute things simply make us want to nurture them.

00:02:26.000 --> 00:02:34.000
Because human babies are relatively helpless on their own. It's hypothesized that evolution favored infants who are perceived as cute and inspired more care and interaction.

00:02:38.000 --> 00:02:43.824
