some scientists have noted a phenomenon called domestication syndrome,

00:02:56.000 --> 00:03:02.720
where certain animals appear to have gradually adopted more juvenile features as they became more docile.

00:03:05.000 --> 00:03:11.784
One theory is that these physical changes are regulated by an embryonic structure called the neural crest.

00:03:12.000 --> 00:03:17.696
It helps determine how some of a developing embryo cells differentiate and where they go.

00:03:18.000 --> 00:03:26.000
Delaying or inhibiting the arrival of the cells in certain areas of the body can result in an under development of the pituitary and adrenal glands, which govern fear and aggression.

00:03:31.000 --> 00:03:37.080
It can also lead to physical characteristics like floppy ears, shorter snouts and smaller jaws.

00:03:39.000 --> 00:03:47.000
This is one idea of how selecting for behavioral characteristics like friendliness, may also select for more juvenile, cuter, physical traits.

00:03:50.000 --> 00:03:53.584
Basically, as humans bred and domesticated, docile dogs,

00:03:55.000 --> 00:03:58.520
we seem to have made some breeds look more like babies.

